The Nigerian Youth Compact on COVID-19 (NYCC) has assured that it will provide a minimum data of 10 million youths across the 774 local government areas in the country, to curtail the effect of the virus. National chairman of NYCC, Comrade Gambo Haruna, stated this on a live streaming programme organised by NYCC tagged: “One Stop Youth Talk” in Abuja yesterday. He said the NYCC was sure of achieving the data via: data gathering, advocacy, capacity building, access and resource in accordance with the United Nations Global Compact on Humanitarian Action and COVID-19. Haruna emphasized the importance of data in planning and the fight against coronavirus. He stressed the need to tackle post COVID-19 panacea which he said was more threatening to the youths. ‘’Without proper planning to cushion the aftermath of the pandemic there is a looming danger,’’ he said. He said it would be a worthless effort if meaningful and accurate data of youths were not properly documented as they would be the most to  hit during the post COVID-19 for constituting more than 60 per cent of the population and also drive the economy of Nigeria. The chairman expressed satisfaction with the massive inflow of youths into the NYCC website to upload their data.